â—¼Shell Scripting: It is a program that allows us to specify tasks to be performed in the form of scripts. These tasks are written in the form of commands in a script file with .sh extension. Scripting file automates the commands written in it line by line whenever it executes. Hence, shell scripting is used to avoid repetitive work. It also saves time as the script that is most frequently used can be written once and executed n number of times. 

â—¼To write #shellscripting follow these steps:
ğŸ“ŒCreate a file using any editor with â€˜.shâ€™ extension and write the script in it line by line. Save the file and exit.
$ vim file_script.sh

ğŸ“ŒAlways remember that the first line of a shell scripting file is always:
#!/bin/bash 
Which is known as #shebang.
ğŸ‘‰Now, the question was can we use sh instead of bash in the first line? 
Bash stands for â€˜Bourne Again SHellâ€™ where as Sh is simply SHell. 
I tried using it and found it working well with some of the commands only while others resulted in an exception. 
Hence, Bash is a superset of sh which supports feature of sh and offers more extensions on top of that. You will expect bash behaviour if you work in #!/bin/bash. 

ğŸ“ŒBy default the file is in rw- mode for user. So, to execute it; change the mode to rwx for user.
$ chmod 700 file_script.sh
You can check the file mode by using
$ls -la

ğŸ“ŒNow execute the script:
$ bash file_script.sh
This file can be run by using sh, ./, . instead of bash.

